Introduction

The GTD is an open-source database that contains collected information on terrorist attacks around the world from 1970 through 2017. The GTD has 137 features and over 180,000 observations.

Part 1 - Classification

Choose the response (target) variable

The response variable we have chosen is the amount of people that have been affect by an incident. The variable wasnt present in the database, so we created the variable by summing the number of people wounded and number of people killed in an incidence. We have focused on this as a target variable to help classify terror attacks as either people will be affected by an attack or they will not be. The labels we assigned to this variable are [0.1) for no-one affect or [1,Inf] for people have been wounded or killed. Our hope is to create a classification model that, with a variety of explanatory variables, will be able to assess if an incident will involve extra attention due to casualties being involved.

Create a categorical target variable. Were there killed or injured people?

Selecting variables

Creating a selection of candidate columns as predictors and the target column. We want to look at a variety of variables that could identify if any has been affected by the event. We use the code book located at https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/downloads/Codebook.pdf to make an informed decision about the variable we could use. The main objective was to chose variables that service operator could have available to them, and then using the model created to make an informed decision on the amount of people affected. For example, we have include the success metric because if the incident was foiled less people will be affected, however, even successful incidents dont always have a human toll.

Splitting the data

Split into train-calibration-test sets, this split is based on the years. We will be creating a model base on data prior to 2013 and using data post 2015 to validate our models. The reasoning behind this split is our model will be designed to predict if future events can be accurately categorised.

split.train.cal.test <- function(x, split.column='iyear', train.split.value=2013, cal.split.value=2015){
  rvalue <- x[,split.column]
  list( x[rvalue <= train.split.value, ],
        x[rvalue > train.split.value & rvalue <= cal.split.value, ],
        x[rvalue > cal.split.value, ])
}

splits <- split.train.cal.test(data, split.column='iyear', train.split.value=2013, cal.split.value=2015)

Here is a function that is used for Single variable predictions for categorical variables.

mkPredC <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol, pos=pos.label) {
  pPos <- sum(outCol==pos)/length(outCol)
  naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]))
  pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
  vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol),varCol)
  pPosWv <- (vTab[pos,]+1.0e-3*pPos)/(colSums(vTab)+1.0e-3)
  pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
  pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
  pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
  pred
}
for(v in catVars) {
  pii <- paste('pred',v,sep='')
  dTrain[,pii] <- mkPredC(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dTrain[,v])
  dCal[,pii] <- mkPredC(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dCal[,v])
  dTest[,pii] <- mkPredC(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dTest[,v])
}

calcAUC <- function(predcol, outcol, pos=pos.label) {
  perf <- performance(prediction(predcol, outcol==pos),'auc')
  as.numeric(perf@y.values)
}

Build single variable predictions for numerical variables. Evaluate AUC for the single-variable models (numericals)

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
mkPredN <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol) {
  cuts <- unique(as.numeric(quantile(varCol, probs=seq(0, 1, 0.1), na.rm=T)))
  varC <- cut(varCol, cuts)
  appC <- cut(appCol, cuts)
  mkPredC(outCol, varC, appC)
}
for(v in numericVars) {
  pii<-paste('pred',v,sep='')
  dTrain[,pii] <- mkPredN(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dTrain[,v])
  dTest[,pii] <- mkPredN(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dTest[,v])
  dCal[,pii] <- mkPredN(dTrain[,outcome], dTrain[,v], dCal[,v])
  aucTrain <- calcAUC(dTrain[,pii],dTrain[,outcome])
  
  if(aucTrain>=0.5) {
    aucCal<-calcAUC(dCal[,pii],dCal[,outcome])
    print(sprintf(
      "%s, trainAUC: %4.3f calibrationAUC: %4.3f",
      pii,aucTrain,aucCal))
  }
}

Perform feature selection with log likelihood

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Define a convenience function to compute log likelihood.
logLikelyhood <- function(outCol, predCol, pos=pos.label) {
  sum(ifelse(outCol==pos, log(predCol), log(1-predCol)))
}
# Compute the base rate of a saturation model
baseRateCheck <- logLikelyhood(dCal[,outcome],  sum(dCal[,outcome]==pos.label)/length(dCal[,outcome]) )

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
selPredVars <- c()
selVars <- c()
minStep <- 1000

for(v in catVars) {
  pii <- paste('pred',v,sep='')
  liCheck <- 2*((logLikelyhood(dCal[,outcome],dCal[,pii])
                 - baseRateCheck))
  if(liCheck>minStep) {
    print(sprintf("%s, calibrationScore: %g",pii,liCheck))
    selPredVars <- c(selPredVars,pii)
    selVars <- c(selVars, v)
  }
}
## [1] "predcountry_txt, calibrationScore: 2636.19"
## [1] "predregion_txt, calibrationScore: 1001.63"
## [1] "predsuccess, calibrationScore: 2365.59"
## [1] "predattacktype1_txt, calibrationScore: 2121.42"

Evaluation of Models

The function below has been created evaluation of the different models we will create. The the function will return an ROC plot, prediction distribution plot, precision/recall plots, a confusion matrix and a null models log likelihood.

evaluate_performance <- function(predictions, true.values, do.print=TRUE, threshold.value=0.5, pos=pos.label){
  eval.auc <- calcAUC(predictions, true.values)
  
  if(do.print){
    # ROC plot
    predObj <- prediction(predictions, true.values)
    perf <- performance(predObj, "tpr", "fpr")
    #plot(performance(predObj, "tpr", "fpr"))
    #abline(0, 1, lty = 2)
    roc.df <- data.frame('fpr'=unlist(perf@x.values),
                   'tpr'=unlist(perf@y.values),
                   'threshold'=unlist(perf@alpha.values))
    
    p <- ggplot(roc.df, aes(x=fpr, y=tpr))+
      geom_line() +
      geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype='dashed') +
      cits4009_theme
    print(p)
    
    # prediction distribution plot
    p <- ggplot(data.frame(predictions=predictions,  true.values=true.values),
          aes(x=predictions, color=true.values, linetype=true.values)) +
          geom_density()  + 
          labs(y = "True Positive Rate", x = "False Positive Rate") +
          cits4009_theme
    
    print(p)
    
    # precision/recall plot
    precObj <- performance(predObj, measure="prec")
    recObj <- performance(predObj, measure="rec")
    precision <- (precObj@y.values)[[1]]
    prec.x <- (precObj@x.values)[[1]]
    recall <- (recObj@y.values)[[1]]
    rocFrame <- data.frame(threshold=prec.x,
                           precision=precision,
                           recall=recall)
    pnull <-mean(true.values==pos)
    
    p1 <- ggplot(rocFrame, aes(x=threshold)) +
    geom_line(aes(y=precision)) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1) )  + cits4009_theme
    p2 <- ggplot(rocFrame, aes(x=threshold)) +
    geom_line(aes(y=recall)) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,1) ) + cits4009_theme
    grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2)
  
    # Confusion matrix table
    cat('Confusion Matrix')
    ctab.test <- table(pred=predictions > threshold.value, true.values=true.values)
    print(kable(ctab.test))
    
    # Log likelihood
    pNull <- mean(true.values==pos.label)
    model.ll <- sum(ifelse(true.values==pos.label, log(predictions), log(1-predictions)))
    null.model.ll <- sum(ifelse(true.values==pos.label, log(pNull), log(1-pNull)))
    print(paste('Model Log Likelihood:', model.ll))
    print(paste('Null Model Log Likelihood:', null.model.ll))
    
  }
  
  eval.auc
}

evaluate_and_log_model <- function(model.type, model.name, predictions.train, true.values.train, predictions.cal, true.values.cal){
  train.auc <- evaluate_performance(predictions.train, true.values.train, do.print = FALSE)
  cal.auc <- evaluate_performance(predictions.cal, true.values.cal, do.print = TRUE)
  result <- data.frame(model.type = model.type,
                         model.name = model.name,
                         train.auc = train.auc,
                         cal.auc = cal.auc)
  rownames(result) <- model.name
  models.auc <<- unique(rbind(models.auc, result))
  result
}

Function use for the one-hot encoding

one_hot<- function(input, output, df_input, check_col, limit) {

  # for variables which have a larger number of factors (pre-selected)
  if (limit > 0){
    x <- as.data.frame(table(df_input[,check_col]))
    # create list of factor not greater than a given frequency
    y <- as.character(c())
    for(i in 1:nrow(x)){
      if(x$Freq[i] < limit){
        y <- c(y, as.character(x$Var1[i]))
      }
    } 
  }
  # subsetting selected colunm(s)   
  temp_df <- subset(df_input, select = input)
  
  #if the factor is in the list, change to Other to limit number of columns
  if (limit > 0){
    for (i in 2:ncol(temp_df)) {
      levels(temp_df[,i])[levels(temp_df[,i]) %in% y] <- 'Other'
    }
  }
  
  # one hot encode, keeping eventid for merging
  setDT(temp_df)
  temp_df <- dcast(setDT(melt(temp_df,id.vars = c("eventid")))[,ind:=1],eventid~value,value.var = "ind",fill=0)
  
  # label other column  
  if("Other" %in% colnames(temp_df)){
    change <- paste('Other_',output,sep='')
    setnames(temp_df, "Other", change)
  }
  
  
  # change values to 1 that may be larger (occured more than once)
  for(j in 2:ncol(temp_df)){
     set(temp_df, i= which(temp_df[[j]] >1), j=j, value =1)
  }
  # check for overflow column
  if("V1" %in% colnames(temp_df)){
    temp_df$V1 <- NULL
  }
  # remove Unknown column (not needed)
  if("Unknown" %in% colnames(temp_df)){
    temp_df$Unknown <- NULL
  }
  # remove NA column (not needed)
  if("NA" %in% colnames(temp_df)){
    temp_df$`NA` <- NULL
  }
  
  temp_df

}

Perform feature selection. In this case we will find the optimal number of features using grid search.

# Take out columns that have just one level in the training set
not.to.use <- names(which((sapply(droplevels(dOHETrain[,catVars]),function(x)length(levels(x))))==1))
to.use <- c(catVars,numericVars)[!( c(catVars,numericVars) %in% not.to.use)]

# Compute the base rate of a saturation model
baseRateCheck <- logLikelyhood(dOHECal[,outcome],  sum(dOHECal[,outcome]==pos.label)/length(dOHECal[,outcome]) )


vars.likelihood.increase <- c()
## ------------------------------------------------------------------------

for(v in catVars[catVars%in%to.use]) {
  pii <- paste('pred',v,sep='')
  liCheck <- 2*((logLikelyhood(dOHECal[,outcome],dOHECal[,pii])
                 - baseRateCheck))
  vars.likelihood.increase[v] <- liCheck
}

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------

for(v in numericVars[numericVars%in%to.use]) {
  pii <- paste('pred',v,sep='')
  liCheck <- 2*((logLikelyhood(dOHECal[,outcome],dOHECal[,pii])
                 - baseRateCheck) - 1)
  vars.likelihood.increase[v] <- liCheck
}
  
vars.likelihood.increase <- sort(vars.likelihood.increase,decreasing = T)

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
bestSelVars <- c()
bestAUC <- 0
for(i in seq(5, length(vars.likelihood.increase), by = 5))
{
  selVars <- names(vars.likelihood.increase)[1:i]
  selPredVars <-  paste('pred',selVars,sep='')
  minStep <- i
  
  fV <- paste(outcome,' ~ .')#,  paste(selVars, collapse=' + '), sep='')
  
  lrmodel <- glm(fV, data=dOHETrain[,c(outcome, selVars)], family = binomial)
  
  auc <- calcAUC(predict(lrmodel,newdata=dOHECal, type='response'), dOHECal[,outcome])
  
  print(sprintf("%d variables selected (at least %f increase in log likelihood). AUC: %f",
                length(selVars), vars.likelihood.increase[i], auc))
  if(auc>bestAUC){
    bestSelVars <- selVars
    bestAUC <- auc
  }
}

The XGBOOST model has a log likelihood of -7309, which is much better than the Null models -14180.97. With an AUC of 0.93 (2.dp) for the testing data which is slightly less than the training data, on which it scored 0.97. The ROC curve of this model looks comparable to the training data, it is definitely a respectable result. The distribution of score broken up by known classes is clearly separated . The precision and the recall looks good,l which was a goal for this model.

Part 2 - Clustering

We will cluster the groups perpetrating the attacks. To this end, we will consider their way of opperation (what type of attacks they make), their location (in which regions they attack), and the lethality of their attacks. Since we care about the relative percentages and not so much about absolute values, we use the cosine similarity. We first calculate the pairwise similarity in each of these three categories, and then create a weighted average to define the similiarity between groups. Since we are working with a distance matrix, we use hierarchical clustering. Note that we will only keep groups with at least 100 attacks on record.

# This function "pivots" a categorical field, grouped by the perpetrating "group"
get.group.actions.pivoted <- function(field, min_count=100){
  field <- as.character(field)
  group.actions <-  attacks %>% 
                    filter(gname != 'Unknown') %>%
                    filter(attacktype1_txt != 'Unknown') %>%
                    group_by(.dots=c('gname',field)) %>% 
                    summarise(cnt = n()) %>%
                    spread(field, cnt, fill = 0) %>%
                    as.data.frame()
  row.names(group.actions) <- group.actions$gname
  group.actions$gname <- NULL
  group.actions[rowSums(group.actions, na.rm=TRUE) > min_count,]
  
}

# A cosine distance (1 - cosine_similarity) matrix calculation
cos.dist <- function(DF){
  Matrix <- as.matrix(DF)
  sim <- Matrix / sqrt(rowSums(Matrix * Matrix))
  sim <- sim %*% t(sim)
  rownames(sim)<-rownames(DF)
  as.dist(1 - sim)
}

# Will use this for plotting (categorical colors)
gg_color_hue <- function(n) {
  hues = seq(15, 375, length = n + 1)
  hcl(h = hues, l = 65, c = 100)[1:n]
}

Now we check the optimal number of clusters using the Calinski-Harabasz (CH) criteria

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Function to calculate squared distance 
# between two vectors x and y
sqr_edist <- function(x, y) {
  sum((x-y)^2)
}

## Fucntion to calculate WSS of a cluster
wss.cluster <- function(clustermat) {
  c0 <- apply(clustermat, 2, FUN=mean)
  sum(apply(clustermat, 1, 
            FUN=function(row){sqr_edist(row,c0)}))
}

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
wss.total <- function(dmatrix, labels) {
  wsstot <- 0
  k <- length(unique(labels))
  for(i in 1:k){
    wsstot <- wsstot + 
      wss.cluster(subset(dmatrix, labels==i))
  }
  wsstot
}

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------
totss <- function(dmatrix) {
  grandmean <- apply(dmatrix, 2, FUN=mean)
  sum(apply(dmatrix, 1, 
            FUN=function(row){
              sqr_edist(row, grandmean)
              }
            )
      )
}


## ----mysize=TRUE, size='\\tiny'------------------------------------------
ch_criterion <- function(dmatrix, d, kmax, method="kmeans") {
  if(!(method %in% c("kmeans", "hclust"))){ 
    stop("method must be one of c('kmeans', 'hclust')")
  }
  npts <- dim(dmatrix)[1] # number of rows.
  totss <- totss(dmatrix)
  wss <- numeric(kmax)
  crit <- numeric(kmax)
  wss[1] <- (npts-1)*sum(apply(dmatrix, 2, var))
  for(k in 2:kmax) {
    if(method=="kmeans") {
      clustering<-kmeans(dmatrix, k, nstart=10, iter.max=100)
      wss[k] <- clustering$tot.withinss
    }else { # hclust
      #d <- dist(dmatrix, method="euclidean")
      pfit <- hclust(d, method="ward.D2")
      labels <- cutree(pfit, k=k)
      wss[k] <- wss.total(dmatrix, labels)
    }
  }
  bss <- totss - wss
  crit.num <- bss/(0:(kmax-1))
  crit.denom <- wss/(npts - 1:kmax)
  crit.num[1] <- 1
  list(crit = (crit.num/crit.denom)[2:kmax], wss = wss[2:kmax], totss = totss[2:kmax], bss = bss[2:kmax])
}

## ------------------------------------------------------------------------

# We use Single Value Decomposition (SVD) to transform the similarity matrix into a feature space
# so that we can calculate the WSS, BSS and tot SS with this proxy
pmatrix <- t(svd(d)$v)[,1:100]

kmax <- 10
clustcrit <- ch_criterion(pmatrix, d, kmax, method="hclust")

critframe <- data.frame(k=2:kmax, ch=scale(clustcrit$crit),
                        wss=scale(clustcrit$wss))

critframe <- melt(critframe, id.vars=c("k"),
                  variable.name="measure",
                  value.name="score")

ggplot(critframe, aes(x=k, y=score, color=measure)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape=measure)) + 
  geom_line(aes(linetype=measure)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=2:kmax, labels=2:kmax) +
  cits4009_theme

plot_pca_clusters <- function(variable_type = 'attacktype1_txt'){
  
  # Scale each row to be in percentages of the group
  group.percentages <- 100*pivoted.data[[variable_type]]/rowSums(pivoted.data[[variable_type]])
  
  fit <- prcomp(group.percentages, scale=T)
  pca.data <- data.frame(row.names=row.names(fit$x), fit$x[,1:2])
  pca.data$cluster <- clusters
  
  cluster.centroids <- pca.data %>% group_by(cluster) %>% summarise_all(mean)
  pca.data$name <- row.names(pca.data)
  
  x="PC1"
  y="PC2"
  PC<-fit
  # PC being a prcomp object
  data <- cluster.centroids
  plot <- ggplot(data, aes_string(x=x, y=y)) +
          geom_point(alpha=1, size=8, aes(color=cluster)) +
          geom_text(alpha=1, size=5, aes(label=cluster), color='black')
  plot <- plot + geom_point(data=pca.data, mapping=aes_string(x=x, y=y, color='cluster'), alpha=0.5, size=3)
  plot <- plot + geom_hline(aes(yintercept=0), size=.2) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=0), size=.2)
  datapc <- data.frame(varnames=rownames(PC$rotation), PC$rotation)
  mult <- min(
      (max(data[,y]) - min(data[,y])/(max(datapc[,y])-min(datapc[,y]))),
      (max(data[,x]) - min(data[,x])/(max(datapc[,x])-min(datapc[,x])))
      )
  datapc <- transform(datapc,
          v1 = 2.25 * mult * (get(x)),
          v2 = 2.25 * mult * (get(y))
          )
  plot <- plot + coord_equal() + geom_text(data=datapc, aes(x=v1, y=v2, label=varnames), size = 5, vjust=1, color="red")
  plot <- plot + geom_segment(data=datapc, aes(x=0, y=0, xend=v1, yend=v2), arrow=arrow(length=unit(0.2,"cm")), alpha=0.75, color="red")
  plot <- plot + ggtitle(paste("PCA for",variable_type))
  plot <- plot + cits4009_theme
  #plot <- plot + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-3,3))
  plot
}
plot_pca_clusters('attacktype1_txt')

Conclusions

Weve used the Global Terrorist Database to fit a predictive classifier that, given an attack information, can decide if people were killed or injured by it. We validated the performance on an out-of-time split of the data. Additionally, we proposed a clustering for the groups perpetrating these acts, based on the way they operate and their locations. When looking at the groups in each cluster and their characteristics, the cluster seems reasonable, and many groups that are known to be similar in motivation and way of operating are grouped together. A possible next step would be to use the group cluster information as a feature for the classifier, since it might encode useful information without the need of having too many levels in the group feature.
